      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Bridge Across the Rio Grande</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Steven Sherman letter on migration from Mexico says immigrants have 'right' to transport their own labor to markets where it can fetch highest price (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mexico's One-Way Remedy'' (Op-Ed, July 18):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mexico's One-Way Remedy'' (Op-Ed, July 18):</p>
        <p>Arguing against an open border with Mexico, proposed by President-elect Vicente Fox, George J. Borjas says, ''The free movement of people is not the same as the free movement of goods.''</p>
        <p>But for most immigrants, as for most people in the world, the labor their bodies can provide is the only good they have to sell.</p>
        <p>It is injustice of the most acute sort to support multinational corporations' ''right'' to sell billions of dollars of goods in every market they want, while denying most people the right to transport the one good they have -- their labor -- to markets where it can fetch the highest price.</p>
        <p>STEVEN SHERMAN  Chapel Hill, N.C., July 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
